The 
Amaryllidaceae
plants are generally bulbous plants, which are widely distributed in the tropical and subtropical regions of the world (

). The family comprises more than 1600 species belonging to about 75 genera (

). The traditional uses of plants of the 
Amaryllidaceae
family are attributed to the exclusive alkaloid chemistry (

). More than 500 alkaloids have been reported from various 
Amaryllidaceae
plants with a wide range of pharmacological activities (

). Members of the 
Amaryllidaceae
plants are well known for their biologically active alkaloids, including galanthamine, which is currently available in the market for the treatment of Alzheimer’ s disease (AD) (

).


Crinum
× 
amabile
Donn ex Ker Gawl. (Amaryllidaceae)

is locally known in Thai as ‘phlap phlueng dok daeng’ or ‘giant lily’ (

). In 
Thailand
, the bulbs of this plant have been traditionally used as diuretics (

). In addition, this plant species has been widely used in Vietnamese folk medicine as an emetic and a remedy for rheumatism and earache (

). Recent phytochemical investigations of this plant showed the presence of haemanthamine-, crinine-, lycorine- and galanthamine-type alkaloids (

; 

, 

; 

). Previous pharmacological evaluations of the extracts and phytochemicals from this plant revealed their cytotoxic, anti-malarial, anti-cholinesterase and anti-inflammatory potentials (

; 

; 

, 

; 

). However, the studies on phytochemicals and biological activities of this plant species have not much been reported.

AD is a neurodegenerative disorder that represents the most common cause of human dementia (

). Cholinergic neurotransmission represents the main approach to impaired cognitive function in AD and dementia patients. In the brain tissue, two cholinesterase enzymes including acetylcholinesterase (AChE) and butyrylcholinesterase (BuChE) play a crucial role in the neurotransmitters imbalance, particularly acetylcholine (ACh). These enzymes contribute to the hydrolytic degradation of ACh in the cerebral cortex and hippocampus. Accordingly, the inhibition of AChE and BuChE is considered a promising strategy for the treatment of AD (

). As part of our ongoing studies on a potential source of ChE inhibitors from Thai medicinal plants, a number of plant species have been screened for AChE and BuChE inhibitory activities. The results showed that the crude extracts of the bulbs of 

C. amabile

exhibited anti-AChE and anti-BuChE potentials. Thus, we report herein the isolation and structure elucidation of seven previously undescribed alkaloids, crinamabilines A–G (
1–7
), two non-alkaloidal compounds, crinamabidiene (
8
) and 6-phenylpiperonyl alcohol (
9
), two first naturally occurring alkaloids, 3-epibuphanisine (
10
) and (+)-1 
β
,2 
β
-epoxy-epicrinine (
11
), along with nineteen known alkaloids 
12–30
(
Fig. 1
). The 
in vitro
AChE and BuChE inhibitory activities of most of the isolated compounds were assessed. The molecular docking studies were successfully performed to illustrate the bindings between the top-scoring alkaloids and the active sites of AChE and BuChE.

