Compound 1 was obtained as a white amorphous solid. The HR-TOFMS (positive ion electrospray ionization, ESI + ) at m/z 288.1243 [M + H] + (calcd. for C 16 H 18 NO 4 , 288.1230) was compatible with the molecular formula C 16 H 17 NO 4 . The IR spectrum indicated the presence of hydroxy ( 3253 cm 1 ), olefinic ( 1654 cm 1 ) and methylenedioxy ( 931 cm 1 ) groups. The 1 H NMR spectrum ( Table 1 , the NMR spectra are in Supplementary data, Fig. S1 S 4 ) showed the presence of two para - oriented aromatic protons as singlets at δ H 6.91 and 6.53 assignable to H-10 and H-7, respectively. The singlet signal at δ H 5.86 could be assigned to the methylenedioxy proton. Two benzylic protons appeared as two doublet resonances at δ H 4.28 and 3.74 ( J = 16.7 Hz) corresponding to H-6. The olefinic proton signals at δ H 6.40 (brd, J = 10.1 Hz) and 6.17 (ddd, J = 10.1, 5.1 and 0.7 Hz) were ascribable to H-1 and H-2, respectively. The small coupling constant (0.7 Hz) was due to the long-range W coupling between the H-2 and the H-4eq (
;
). The presence of one lowfield methine signal at δ H 4.25–4.28 was indicative of a hydroxy group located on C-3. H-4ax and H-4eq appeared at δ H 2.23 (ddd, J = 13.4, 13.4 and 4.4 Hz) and δ H 1.80, dddd, J = 13.4, 4.7, 1.3 and 0.7 Hz), respectively. The small coupling constants between H-3 (W ½ = 11.1 Hz) and both H-4ax (4.4 Hz) and H-4eq (1.3 Hz) were in agreement with the α -ethano bridge and an axial-oriented hydroxy substituent at C-3 (
). The 13 C NMR and DEPT-135 data ( Table 5 , the NMR spectra are in Supplementary data, Fig. S5 S 6) showed the presence of sixteen carbon resonances attributed to five quaternary, seven methine and four methylene carbons. In addition, in the HMBC experiments ( Fig. 2 and Table S1 ), H-1 showed correlations with C-2 ( δ C 133.3), C-3 ( δ C 65.2), C-4a ( δ C 64.1), C-10a ( δ C 137.6) and C-10 b ( δ C 51.8), whereas H-2 correlated with C-4 ( δ C 33.5) and C-10 b. The H-4a ( δ H 3.39, brdd, J = 13.4 and 4.7 Hz) was connected to C-6 ( δ C 62.2), C-10a, C-11 ( δ C 81.5) and C-12 ( δ C 64.3) through three-bonds HMBC interaction. The benzylic protons at position 6 were also correlated with C-4a, C-7 ( δ C 108.3), C-10a and C- 12 in the HMBC spectrum. Moreover, the HMBC correlations between H-7 with C-6, C-9 ( δ C 148.6) and C-10a, and H-10 with C-6a ( δ C 127.4), C-8 ( δ C 148.1), and C-10 b, along with the correlation between methylenedioxy proton and C-8 and C-9, were also observed. The structural assignment for compound 1 was supported by the analysis of its NOESY spectrum ( Fig. 3 ). The H-3eq signal displayed a key interaction with H-4ax, whereas H-4eq correlated with H-4a, suggesting the equatorial-orientation of H-3. Moreover, H-4a displayed key interactions with H-6 β and H-4eq, whereas H-4ax showed a correlation with H-12 exo ( δ H 3.11, dd, J = 13.8 and 3.4 Hz). Moreover, H-6 α correlated with H-12 endo ( δ H 3.41, brdd, J = 13.8 and 7.0 Hz), and H-10 showed a correlation with H-1. The relative configuration of C-11 was also determined by the NOESY relationship with H-12 exo, which indicated an exo disposition of H-11 ( δ H 3.94, ddd, J = 7.0, 3.4 and 0.9 Hz). It should be noted that the presence of very small coupling constants or the broad signals of the H-4a, H-6, H-11 and H-12 resulted from the long-range couplings in this type of core structure (
). As illustrated in Fig. 3 , the findings suggest that C-11 has the R configuration (
). The ECD spectral patterns of the α -ethano and β -ethano bridges have been reported (
;
;
;
;
). A comparison was made between the ECD spectra of vittatine, the α -ethano oriented alkaloid, which showed a negative Cotton effect around 240 nm and a positive Cotton effect around 290 nm , and the β -ethano oriented alkaloid, crinine, which showed Cotton effects at the two wavelengths with opposite signs (
;
). The experimental ECD spectrum of compound 1 ( Fig. 4 ) showed a negative Cotton effect at 244 nm (Δ ε 34.5) and a positive Cotton effect at 294 nm (Δ ε + 31.3), which was in agreement with the haemanthamine-type alkaloid, haemanthamine (
). These observations suggest that the absolute configuration of compound 1 was 3 S ,4a S ,5 R ,10bR,11 R as presented in Fig. 1 . On the basis of these data, the structure of compound 1 was established as shown and was named crinamabiline A.

