). The absolute configuration of 2 was thus determined as 3 S , 4a S ,5 R ,6 S ,10bR,11 R . Based on these data, the structure of compound 2 was established and was named crinamabiline B.

Compound 7 was obtained as a white amorphous solid. The molecular formula C 17 H 21 NO 5 was determined by the HR-TOFMS (ESI + ) at m/ z 320.1491 [M + H] + (calcd. for C 17 H 22 NO 5 , 320.1492). The IR spectrum exhibited the absorption bands of hydroxy ( 3356 cm 1 ) and methylenedioxy ( 933 cm 1 ) groups. The 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of compound 7 ( Tables 3 and 5 , the NMR spectra are in Supplementary data, Fig. S96 S101) showed most spectral patterns similar to those of compound 4 and other compounds, but some differences in spectral patterns were present. The notable difference was the absence of the olefinic proton signals at C-1 and C-2. Additionally, the presence of two coupled methylene protons at δ H 2.58 (ddd, J = 13.5, 4.8 and 2.1 Hz, H-1eq), 1.92 (ddd, J = 13.5, 12.9 and 5.2 Hz, H-1ax), 1.83 (dddd, J = 13.3, 12.9, 11.2 and 4.8 Hz, H-2ax) and 1.97 (brdddd, J = 13.3, 5.2, 4.4 and 2.1 Hz, H-2eq) indicated that compound 7 had an additional hydrogenated residue relative to those of 6-hydroxycrinamine ( 18 ) (
), which has also been isolated from
C. amabile
in the present work. The 13 C NMR data are consistent with these observations ( Table 5 ). The 1 H– 1 H COSY and HMBC experiments ( Fig. 2 ) confirmed the foregoing assignments. The presence of the benzylic proton signal at δ H 4.97 suggested that a hydroxy substituent was located at position 6, which was confirmed by HMBC correlations of H-6 with C-4a ( δ C 60.4), C-7 ( δ C 108.6), C-10a ( δ C 139.7) and C-12 ( δ C 58.1) ( Fig. 2 ). The α -orientation of H-6 was confirmed by the NOESY correlation of this proton with H-12 endo . The configuration of C-11 was established by the NOESY correlations of H-11 ( δ H 4.02, brdd, J = 6.7 and 3.9 Hz) with H-1eq and H-10 ( δ H 6.64), which indicated an endo disposition of H-11. The results, illustrated in Fig. 3 , therefore, suggest that C-11 has the S configuration. The absolute configuration of this alkaloid was determined from the ECD experiment, which showed a negative Cotton effect at 246 nm (Δ ε 33.2) and a positive Cotton effect at 280 nm (Δ ε + 20.8), which is in agreement with compound 19 . As the endo disposition of H-11 does not exert a considerable effect on the ECD spectrum (
;
;
), the similar ECD curve of compound 7 ( Fig. 4 ) compared with those of compounds 1–6 has led to a conclusion that the absolute configuration of compound 7 is an α -ethano oriented alkaloid (
;
;
). The absolute configuration of 7 was elucidated as 3 R ,4a S ,5 R ,6 S ,10bR,11 S . On the basis of these findings, compound 7 was concluded as crinamabiline G.

Compound 10 was obtained as a white amorphous solid. The HR-TOFMS (ESI + ) at m/z 286.1432 [M + H] + (calcd. for C 17 H 20 NO 3 , 286.1437) was compatible with the molecular formula C 17 H 19 NO 3 . The IR spectrum indicated the presence of olefinic ( 1644 cm 1 ) and methylenedioxy ( 932 cm 1 ) groups. The 1 H NMR spectra ( Table 3 , the NMR spectra are in Supplementary data, Fig. S132 S135) showed the presence of a 1,2,4,5-tetrasubstituted aromatic ring and the methylenedioxy group, which are characteristic of the aromatic ring of the alkaloids found in this plant species. Two doublets at δ H 4.47 and 3.85 (each J = 17.0 Hz) are indicative of the unsubstituted C-6 benzylic carbon. The olefinic proton signals at δ H 6.61 (brd, J = 10.0 Hz) and 6.00 (dd, J = 10.0 and 5.2 Hz) were ascribable to H-1 and H-2, respectively. The presence of one deshielded methine signal at δ H 3.83–3.87 (m, W ½ = 20.5 Hz) and a methoxy signal at δ H 3.88 (s) was noted. The ECD experiment of 10 has thus been determined and it was found that its ECD curve exhibited opposite Cotton effects to those of compounds 1–7 with a positive Cotton effect at 244 nm (Δ ε + 24.0) and a negative Cotton effect at 294 nm (Δ ε 22.8) ( Fig. 4 ), which was in agreement with the crinine-type alkaloid (
). The large coupling constants between H-3ax and both H-4 ( δ H 2.22 and 1.64) were in agreement with an β -ethano bridge and an equatorial-oriented methoxy substituent at C-3. The HMBC spectrum ( Fig. 2 ) confirmed the methoxy group was placed at C-3. The structural assignment for compound 10 was supported by the analysis of its NOESY spectrum ( Fig. 3 ). The NOESY experiments thus confirmed the relative configuration of compound 10 . A comparison was made between the ECD spectra of the β -ethano oriented crinine, which showed a positive Cotton effect around 240 nm and a negative Cotton effect around 290 nm , and the α -ethano oriented vittatine, which showed Cotton effects at the two wavelengths with opposite signs (
). These observations suggest that the absolute configuration of 10 is as shown in Fig. 1 . Compound 10 , epibuphanisine, has been mentioned as one of the products in the synthesis of crinine analogs (
), but no information about this compound was provided. It should be noted that the name of the synthetic compound given by the previous work may lead to confusion since this name has already been used for compound 12 previously isolated (
) and this compound has also been isolated from
C. amabile
in this study. We therefore suggest that the alkaloid 10 should be named 3-epibuphanisine. This compound has therefore been isolated from a natural source for the first time.

Compound 11 was isolated as a white amorphous solid and was assigned the molecular formula C 16 H 17 NO 4 as determined from the HR-TOFMS (ESI + ) at m/z 288.1255 [M + H] + (calcd. for C 16 H 18 NO 4 , 288.1230). The IR spectrum indicated the presence of hydroxy ( 3356 cm 1 ), epoxide ( 1284 cm 1 ) and methylenedioxy ( 934 cm 1 ) moieties. The 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of compound 11 ( Tables 3 and 5 , the NMR spectra are in Supplementary data, Fig. S148 S153) displayed similar spectral features to those of compound 10 , except two olefinic proton signals in compound 10 were replaced by two oxygenated methine signals at δ H 3.89 (d, J = 3.5 Hz) and δ H 3.26 (brdd, J = 3.5 and 2.7 Hz) assignable to H-1 and H-2, respectively. These NMR spectral data, together with the evidence from the HR-TOFMS, indicate that the double bond at C-1 and C-2 is epoxidized. The conformation of the epoxide ring was assigned from the small coupling constants of H-1 with H-2 ( J = 3.5 Hz) and H-2 with H-3 ( J = 2.7 Hz). In addition, a deshielded methine proton at δ H 4.37–4.43 (m, W ½ = 21.0 Hz) was observed. The HMBC correlations from H-2 and H-4a to C-3 ( δ C 65.9) unambiguously placed the hydroxy group at C-3 ( Fig. 2 and Table S3 ). The NOESY correlation (see Fig. 3 ) between H-3 and H-4a ( δ H 3.40, brdd, J = 10.5 and 6.1 Hz) was in agreement with an equatorial-oriented hydroxy substituent at C-3. Comparison of the 1 H NMR spectral features with those of flexinine ( 21 ) (
), which has been isolated from this plant species in the present work, reveals that they closely resemble; the notable difference being the small W ½ value (9.1 Hz) of compound 21 that indicates the equatorial-orientation of H-3. The absolute configuration of this alkaloid was determined from the ECD experiments ( Fig. 4 ). As expected, the ECD curve of compound 11 exhibited a similar positive Cotton effect at 249 nm (Δ ε + 31.5) and a negative Cotton effect at 279 nm (Δ ε 9.1) to those of compound 10 . Compound 11 has previously been reported as a synthetic compound, (+)-1 β ,2 β -epoxy-epicrinine (
;
) and it has therefore been first reported from a natural source in this study.

In the previous reports, a variety of genera in the Amaryllidaceae family including
Galanthus
,
Narcissus
,
Rhodophiala
,
Zephyranthes
and
Crinum
revealed the different structural types of alkaloids. The members of galanthamine-, lycorine- and haemanthamine-type alkaloids are the most abundant Amaryllidaceae plants, which have superior AChE inhibitory activities, especially, an AChEI galanthamine was approved by the FDA for treatment of AD revealing possibilities for structural modification or semi-synthesis of potent AChEIs. Alkaloid extracts and fractions of about 100 species of 20 genera resulted in more than 200 Amaryllidaceae alkaloids that have been studied for their in vitro AChE inhibitory activity. Some of these alkaloids have been studied in silico to study the interactions between Amaryllidaceae alkaloids and the AChE enzyme (
;
;
). For example, compounds 17–20 , 22 , 24 , 25 , 27–30 have been reported for their AChE inhibitory activity evaluation (
;
; Cahlíkova´et al., 2013;
). Thus, the Amaryllidaceae alkaloids prompt the interest of researchers as promising compounds that deserve further in vitro and in vivo study to reveal new AD drugs.

In this study, most of the isolated compounds were evaluated for their AChE and BuChE inhibitory activities by the method described previously by our group (Chaichompoo et al., 2021) and the results are shown in Table 6 . Galanthamine, the well-known AChE and BuChE inhibitor, was used as the reference drug. The alkaloid ungeremine (2 9 ) exhibited the strongest inhibitory activity against AChE, with the IC 50 values of 0.21 μM, which was about 6-fold more active than galanthamine (IC 50 1.23 μM), followed by compound 19 , which showed similar inhibitory activity (IC 50 1.86 μM) to that of galanthamine. Compounds 16 and 28 showed high inhibitory activities with the IC 50 values of 6.41 and 7.08 μM, followed by compounds 7 , 10 , 12 , 15 , 18 , 20 and 21 and 23–27 , which exhibited moderate to weak AChE inhibitory activity with the IC 50 values ranging from 16.76 to 99.51 μM. In addition, alkaloid 29 also displayed the highest BuChE inhibitory activity among the tested alkaloids, with the IC 50 value of 3.57 μM, which was slightly less active than galanthamine (IC 50 3.11 μM). Furthermore, compounds 10 , 12 , 15 , 16 , 18–21 , 23, 24 and 26 showed good to low degrees of BuChE inhibitory activity with IC 50 values of 9.31–247.57 μM, whereas compounds 7 , 25 , 27 and 28 were inactive to the anti-BuChE assay. The tested compounds included two types of alkaloids, the crinane- and lycorine-type alkaloids (
). As the number of each member of the compounds and the structural diversity of each type of the alkaloids are somewhat limited, a detailed structure–anti-ChE activity relationship (SAR) study could not be concluded. However, a preliminary SAR study revealed that, for the crinane-type alkaloids, the presence of the 6-hydroxy group seemed to enhance both AChE and BuChE inhibitory activities. Comparing the structures of 6-hydroxycrinamine ( 19 ) with that of galanthamine, the two compounds have comparable sizes. However, the presence of the 6-hydroxy group might contribute to its high AChE inhibitory activity since crinamine ( 18 ) was only approximately 18-folds less active than 19 . Moreover, the α -hydroxyamino function in 19 might also exist in the form of the open-ring amino aldehyde function under the test condition (
;
) and might contribute to the high activity of 19 . However, further study is required to verify this postulate. For the lycorine-type alkaloids, the high potency of compound 29 was attributed to the presence of the ring C aromatic connected to the quaternary ammonium functionality, which is important for ChE inhibitory activities. For comparison with galanthamine, the presence of a nitrogen atom connected to the ring C aromatic seemed to be similar to active pharmacophores to those of
29 in
ChE inhibitory activities (
;
). The observation was confirmed by molecular docking results.

Optical rotations were measured on a JASCO-1020 polarimeter. Electronic Circular Dichroism (ECD) was recorded on a JASCO J-810 spectropolarimeter. IR spectra were recorded in the ATR mode using a PerkinElmer FT-IR Spectrum 400 spectrophotometer. 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra were recorded at 25 ◦ C on a Bruker ASCEND 400 FT-NMR spectrometer, operating at 400 MHz and 100 MHz for 1 H and 13 C NMR, respectively. Chemical shift values are depicted as δ values in parts per million (ppm) and were indirectly referenced to tetramethylsilane (TMS) via the solvent residual signals δ H 7.24 and δ C 77.00 for CDCl 3 ; δ H 3.30 and δ C 49.50 for CD 3 OD. The coupling constants are expressed as J in Hz. HR-TOFMS spectra were measured with a Bruker micrOTOF-QII mass spectrometer, using electrospray ionization (ESI, positive ion mode) as the ionization technique. Unless otherwise indicated, column chromatography was carried out using Merck silica gel 60 (particle sizes less than 0.063 mm ) and Merck silica gel 60 RP-18 (particle sizes
0.040 –0.063 mm
). The slurry method of column packing has been employed. For thin-layer chromatography (TLC), Merck pre-coated silica gel 60 F 254 plates were used. Spots on TLC were detected under UV light and by spraying with anisaldehyde-H 2 SO 4 reagent and Dragendorff’ s reagent followed by heating.

