The inhibitory activities of the crude extracts and isolated compounds on AChE and BuChE were conducted using Ellman’ s method (
) with minor modifications mentioned in the previous report (Chaichompoo et al., 2021). The enzymes and chemicals including AChE (from
Electrophorus electricus
), BuChE (from equine serum), galanthamine (as hydrobromide salt), 5,5 ′ -dithiobis (2-nitrobenzoic acid) (DTNB), bovine serum albumin (BSA), acetylthiocholine iodide (ATCI) and S -butyrylthiocholine iodide (BTCI) were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich (St. Louis, Missouri , USA ). Briefly, the enzyme solutions were prepared at 0.2 U/mL in 10 mM phosphate buffer solution (PBS, pH 8.0). The assay medium consisted of 140 μL of 10 mM PBS, 20 μL of the enzyme and 20 μL of the test compounds were mixed in a 96-well plate and shaken for 10 min. The reaction was initiated by the addition of 20 μL of a mixture of 5 mM DTNB, 0.1% BSA, and substrate (ATCI or BTCI) and was then incubated at room temperature for 5 min. The absorbance was measured using a microplate reader (Sunrise, Switzerland ) at a wavelength of 405 nm . The percentage of AChE inhibition was calculated by comparing the rate of enzymatic hydrolysis of ASCI for the sample to that of the blank (80% MeOH in buffer). The percentage of BuChE inhibition was similarly performed as described for AChE. Galanthamine was used as a positive control. All experiments were conducted in triplicate and IC 50 values were calculated by linear regression.

The molecular docking technique was applied to study the binding orientation and affinity of the alkaloid 29 from the bulbs of
Crinum × amabile
toward the binding gorge of AChE and BuChE enzymes using Autodock 4.2 (
). The compound was created with the program ACD Lab and then optimized by Hartree-Fock level calculations with the 6-31G* basis set using the GAUSSIAN09 package (
). The 3D protein structures of the human AChE and human BuChE enzymes were obtained from the Protein Data Bank with PDB IDs: 4EY6 and 4BDS, respectively. Galanthamine, used as a control molecule, was re-docked into the AChE binding site to determine the appropriate binding parameters for docking. Proteins were processed using AutoDock Tools (
) to remove all water molecules and generate all hydrogen atoms of the molecule. Nonpolar hydrogen atoms and lone pairs were then merged and Gasteiger partial charges were assigned to each atom. A grid box of 80 × 80 × 80 points with a spacing of 0.375 Å was positioned at the center of the active site gorge. The protein molecule was kept rigid while the ligand was flexible. The autogrid4 parameter was used to attain grid maps. Furthermore, autodock4 was performed using Lamarckian genetic algorithms to obtain the best docking conformation. For each docking experiment, 250 independent docking runs were performed. The conformations were selected based on the lowest binding energy in the cluster with the most %conformations (see Table S5 ). They were then compared to their experimental IC 50 values to confirm relative accuracy. Analysis and visualization of the docking results were done using the BIOVIA Discovery studio visualizer (BIOVIA, Dassault Syst`emes, 2019).
